### 4.2 The binding‑changed handler

```cpp
static void binding_table_changed(const chip::ChipDeviceEvent *event, intptr_t /*arg*/)
{
    // The binding table lives inside the server; we can query it directly.
    // This callback is invoked **after** the server has already updated the table,
    // so we can read the current contents safely.
    const chip::Binding::BindingTable &table = chip::Server::GetInstance().GetBindingTable();

    // Walk the whole table and decide what to do with each entry.
    for (size_t i = 0; i < table.Size(); ++i) {
        const chip::Binding::BindingEntry &entry = table[i];
        if (!entry.IsValid()) {
            // Invalid entries are “holes” – ignore them.
            continue;
        }

        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        // 1️⃣  Filter: we only care about bindings that target
        //     the BooleanState cluster on the remote side.
        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        if (entry.remote.cluster != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Id) {
            ESP_LOGI(TAG,
                     "Skipping binding %zu – remote cluster 0x%04X not BooleanState",
                     i, entry.remote.cluster);
            continue;
        }

        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        // 2️⃣  Check if we already have a subscription for this entry.
        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        if (shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().Find(entry) != nullptr) {
            // Already subscribed – nothing to do.
            continue;
        }

        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        // 3️⃣  Validate the fabric (optional – you may want to accept
        //     only a specific fabric index, e.g. the one we are
        //     commissioned on).  For demo we accept any fabric.
        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        // if (entry.fabric_index != chip::Server::GetInstance().GetFabricTable().GetPrimaryFabricIndex()) {
        //     ESP_LOGW(TAG, "Rejecting binding from foreign fabric %u", entry.fabric_index);
        //     // Remove the entry – the spec says the server must reject it.
        //     chip::Server::GetInstance().GetBindingTable().RemoveAt(i);
        //     continue;
        // }

        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        // 4️⃣  All checks passed – ask the manager to start a subscription.
        // ---------------------------------------------------------
        esp_err_t rc = shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().AddBinding(entry);
        if (rc != ESP_OK) {
            ESP_LOGE(TAG,
                     "Failed to start subscription for binding %zu: %s",
                     i,
                     esp_err_to_name(rc));
            // Optionally delete the entry so the user sees it failed.
            // chip::Server::GetInstance().GetBindingTable().RemoveAt(i);
        }
    }

    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    // Cleanup of removed entries:
    // Walk the subscription map and delete any entry that no longer
    // appears in the binding table (user removed it manually).
    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    std::vector<chip::Binding::BindingEntry> current_entries;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < table.Size(); ++i) {
        const auto &e = table[i];
        if (e.IsValid())
            current_entries.push_back(e);
    }

    // Copy the map keys to avoid holding the lock while we call RemoveBinding.
    std::vector<chip::Binding::BindingEntry> to_remove;
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().m_mutex);
        for (const auto &kv : shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().m_subs) {
            // Decode the key back to the three fields
            uint64_t raw = kv.first;
            uint8_t fab   = (raw >> 56) & 0xFF;
            uint64_t nid  = (raw >> 8)  & 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFULL;
            uint16_t ep   = raw & 0xFF;
            bool found = false;
            for (const auto &e : current_entries) {
                if (e.fabric_index == fab &&
                    e.remote.node_id == nid &&
                    e.remote.endpoint == ep) {
                    found = true;
                    break;
                }
            }
            if (!found) {
                chip::Binding::BindingEntry dead{};
                dead.fabric_index = fab;
                dead.remote.node_id = nid;
                dead.remote.endpoint = ep;
                to_remove.push_back(dead);
            }
        }
    }

    for (const auto &dead : to_remove) {
        shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().RemoveBinding(dead);
    }
}
```

**Explanation of the flow**

* The **binding table event** fires *after* the server has updated its internal table, so we can safely read it.
* We **filter** for entries that point to the `BooleanState` cluster (your contact sensor). If you want to allow **any** cluster you can drop that check.
* **Optional fabric constraint** – uncomment the code block if you want to reject bindings that belong to a different fabric (e.g. you only want the primary fabric).
* For each *new* entry we call `SubscriptionManager::AddBinding`. The manager:
  * Opens a CASE session,
  * Performs a quick read to verify the attribute exists,
  * If the read succeeds, it upgrades to a **subscription** that will keep feeding you `OnAttributeData` callbacks.
* When a binding is **removed** (user clears it in the controller UI) the same event fires. The handler walks the map of active subscriptions, finds any that are **no longer present** in the table, and calls `RemoveBinding` – which aborts the `ReadClient` and frees the memory.

