## 6. Full integration checklist

| ✅ Item | What you have to add / verify |
|------|--------------------------------|
| **Binding manager init** | Call `esp_matter::client::binding_manager_init();` **once** after `esp_matter::start()` (or before, but after the Matter thread is up). |
| **Request callback** | `esp_matter::client::set_request_callback()` is already used inside `SubscriptionManager::AddBinding`. No global callback is needed. |
| **ReadClient callback** | Implemented as `BooleanStateSubscriptionCallback`. It receives `bool` values and calls your driver (`app_driver_shade_open/stop`). |
| **Subscription lifetime** | Owned by `SubscriptionManager` (a `unique_ptr`). `RemoveBinding` aborts and clears it. |
| **Thread‑safety** | All map accesses guarded by `std::mutex`. Callbacks run on the Matter thread, so no extra dispatch is required. |
| **Error handling & retry** | In `OnError` we simply log and let the manager retry by re‑calling `AddBinding` after a short back‑off (you can add a timer if you like). The example currently just logs – you can extend it. |
| **Constraint enforcement** | In `binding_table_changed` you can add any rule before calling `AddBinding`. To *reject* an entry, call `chip::Server::GetInstance().GetBindingTable().RemoveAt(i);` and return. |
| **Resource cleanup on reboot** | All subscriptions are rebuilt automatically because the binding table is persisted in NVS. When the device boots, the `kBindingsChangedViaCluster` event fires for each persisted entry, and the manager will re‑create the subscriptions. |
| **Driver hooks** | Replace the placeholder `app_driver_shade_open()` / `app_driver_shade_stop()` with your actual GPIO logic (you already have `GPIO_OUTPUT_COVER_OPEN`, etc.). |
| **Logging** | All important steps use `ESP_LOGI/E/W`. Adjust the tag/verbosity as you need. |

