## 4. Updated binding‑changed event handler (the only caller)

Replace the old `binding_table_changed()` implementation with the **new** version that uses the two‑step API:

```cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// In app_main.cpp (or wherever you handle kBindingsChangedViaCluster)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
static void binding_table_changed(const chip::ChipDeviceEvent * /*event*/, intptr_t /*arg*/)
{
    const chip::Binding::BindingTable &table = chip::Server::GetInstance().GetBindingTable();

    // Temporary map that will receive all *current* subscriptions.
    std::map<uint64_t, std::unique_ptr<shade::Subscription>> new_subs;

    // -------------------------------------------------------------
    // Walk the whole table – for every *valid* entry call AddBinding().
    // -------------------------------------------------------------
    for (size_t i = 0; i < table.Size(); ++i) {
        const chip::Binding::BindingEntry &entry = table[i];
        if (!entry.IsValid())
            continue;   // empty slot

        // Accept only BooleanState cluster on the remote side.
        if (entry.remote.cluster != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Id) {
            ESP_LOGI(TAG,
                     "Skipping binding %zu – remote cluster 0x%04X not BooleanState",
                     i,
                     entry.remote.cluster);
            continue;
        }

        // Let the manager decide whether to reuse or create a new subscription.
        esp_err_t rc = shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().AddBinding(entry, new_subs);
        if (rc != ESP_OK) {
            ESP_LOGE(TAG,
                     "AddBinding failed for entry %zu: %s",
                     i,
                     esp_err_to_name(rc));
            // The manager already cleaned up any partially‑created object.
        }
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------
    // After the loop finishes, tell the manager to discard everything
    // that is no longer present.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------
    shade::SubscriptionManager::Instance().FinishAdditions(new_subs);
}
```

**What changed compared to the original design**

* **No mutexes** – the manager’s internal map is accessed only from this single event‑handler thread, so we can safely omit locking for now.
* **All ownership moves are explicit** – `std::unique_ptr` guarantees that every `Subscription` lives exactly once.
* **Removal logic is centralized** – `FinishAdditions()` automatically aborts any subscription that disappeared from the table, so you no longer need a separate “scan for removed entries” loop.

